87,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The spec explicitly says 'two instances', which means separate processes. While in-process async/await against a shared database *might* trigger race conditions if the code uses DB-level locking, it would miss failures related to process-specific semantics or session state. The real failure—two processes both applying the same migration—can only be reliably reproduced with actual concurrent processes competing for the database. You need the full production scenario: process spawning, startup synchronization, real database locking, and OS-level behavior to expose timing bugs.","test_description":"System test that spawns two Node.js processes (or threads), both running the migration runner against the same PostgreSQL database. Use a synchronization mechanism (e.g., a named pipe or shared lock file) to ensure both processes start at approximately the same time. Provide a set of migration files. Let both processes run concurrently. Verify: (1) each migration is recorded exactly once in `_migrations` (no duplicate entries), (2) both processes complete without error or deadlock, (3) the final database schema is correct (all migrations applied exactly once). This requires actual concurrent access patterns and real database locking behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.6,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A unit test with a mocked DB could verify the code makes a CREATE TABLE call, but wouldn't catch real failures: the CREATE TABLE statement is malformed, the 